items.prompt: Though she made the cut years ago, its figurative scars would never what?
items.response:
He paused, trying to think of the right word. Scarred? Wounded? She had been through so much, and yet here she was, still standing. Still fighting. Still determined to make the world a better place.

He loved her for it.

He loved her for it so much it hurt.

He loved her for it so much he couldn't bear to lose her again.

"I love you, too," he whispered.

She smiled, and it was the same smile he had fallen in love with all those years ago. The same smile that had made him weak in the knees. The same smile that had made him want to take the world on with her by his side.

"I love you, too," she said again, and this time, he heard the tears in her voice.

He stood and pulled her into his arms, holding her tight. He had waited a lifetime for this moment, and he wasn't going to let her go so soon. Not when she was still fighting. Not when she was still determined to make the world a better place.

He kissed her gently on the forehead. "I'll be right here," he promised.

She nodded, and he watched her walk away, her shoulders back, her head held high. He watched her until she disappeared into the crowd, and then he turned to face the stage.

He had waited a lifetime for this moment, too.

He walked up the stairs and took his place in the front row. He had always wanted to see her perform, and now he was here, watching her perform in front of the entire world.

She was amazing.

She was perfect.

She was his.

She was his forever.

He leaned forward, resting his elbows on his knees, and let the music wash over him. He had waited a lifetime for this moment, too.

He was going to love every minute of it.
